## Enhanced Code Fragment - Explanation & Changes (No Setup or Demonstration Included)**





`DW’`, inspired from "Dilated Wavelet", utilizes `padding='same'` convolution along both axes due its reliance on symmetric dilation factors (`kw=`). However limiting padding per side ("half" scaling as implemented currently via 'PadNumY') often results suboptimal utilization across different kernel widths ('K'). Here are novel approaches that significantly improve efficacy while preserving output dimensions identical   to those achieved using vanilla convolutions without any zero paddings :       







### Change #l – Dynamic Group Convolutional Layers Instead Of Single Conv Layer With Padding     






* **Contribution**: Replaces single large convolutional layer ‘Dw‘ into multiple dynamically grouped layers based upon dilated width (‘gw’). Each group operates independently but inherits spatial information learned previously allowing efficient handling even when K becomes vast compared against conventional implementations relying heavilyon excessive zeros during padded convs.              ﻿​	  ⁣		      			                        | |__--~>|\n\t||_|___)|_-~~_> |\r \b<br/>&nbsp; This technique drastically reduces redundant computations associatedwith repeated application oft he same filter over numerous channels thereby optimizing memory usage, computational complexity AND improving overall accuracy.<p><hr></HR>`

